            "description": "If circuit breakers trip repeatedly, you may have overloaded circuits—too many devices drawing power simultaneously from one circuit. Unplug all devices from the affected circuit. Reset the tripped breaker. Gradually plug devices back in one at a time, waiting a few minutes between each. If the breaker trips when you add a specific device, that device may be faulty. If the breaker trips when you reach a certain number of devices, the circuit is overloaded and needs professional attention—either redistribute loads to other circuits or install additional circuits. Never use extension cords or power strips as permanent solutions for overloaded circuits. Common overload culprits include space heaters, hair dryers, microwaves, and window AC units all running on the same circuit. Call professionals to add dedicated circuits for high-draw appliances.",
